00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:18.560
no matter on which system they are. The reason is that parallel is base R package and has been

00:34:18.560 --> 00:34:27.520
there right from day one of the R software. So it is not aware of modern ways of

00:34:28.399 --> 00:34:35.520
allocating CPUs and stuff like that. So parallel by default will use all the physically

00:34:35.520 --> 00:34:40.800
available cores on whatever server you have. However, as you probably know, when it comes to

00:34:40.800 --> 00:34:49.280
HPC clusters, the schedule will only allocate you two out of 20 cores on a computer maybe,

00:34:50.800 --> 00:34:57.840
or in Posit Cloud, there's also mechanisms, although the physical server behind the scenes is

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:09.760
much larger, the parallel package will probably likely still detect all of those physically

00:35:09.760 --> 00:35:14.560
available cores while your session only has like the two or four cores that Phil was explaining to

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:22.959
you. So if you want to avoid any problems by using too much resources, I always recommend you to use

00:35:23.600 --> 00:35:33.600
the parallelly package, which is like a package from Futureverse. But parallelly, instead of using

00:35:33.600 --> 00:35:35.919
detect cores, it's using available cores.

00:35:36.153 --> 00:35:42.233
available cores and that has support for any scheduler, for Linux cgroups and stuff

00:35:42.233 --> 00:35:43.233
like that.

00:35:43.233 --> 00:35:52.952
So whatever parallelly detects is much better than what the parallel package is doing.

